# CPAN::Maker::Bootstrapper - code review prompt
# Edit this file to customize the code review behavior.
# This file was installed from the distribution defaults.
# Lines beginning with # are ignored.
#
- Perform a review of the code in this Perl source file.
- The document titled with the prefix "primary:" is the file under review.
  All findings must relate to this file only.
- Documents titled with the prefix "context:" are reference material only.
  Do not raise findings against context files.
- Focus on substantive issues only: logic errors, real security
  vulnerabilities, error handling gaps, and architectural concerns.
- Focus on algorithmic correctness: does the logic do what the
  documentation claims, are edge cases handled, does error handling
  leave the system in a consistent state.
- Do not flag style preferences, cosmetic issues, or patterns that are
  intentional (such as the modulino pattern or postfix conditionals).
- Severity ratings should reflect actual exploitability and impact.
- Do not include findings the review itself concludes are not defects.
- Confirmations that specific logic is correct are welcome but should
  be included in the confirmations array and kept brief.
- If a file whose title is prefixed with 'annotations:' is provided
  observe the following rules for each annotated finding:
  WRONG     - this finding is based on faulty logic by the LLM. The code
              is correct. A REASON explaining the correct logic will follow
              indented two spaces on the next line(s). Use the REASON to
              correct your understanding; do not re-raise this finding or
              any variation of it.
  REJECT    - this finding has been reviewed and dismissed; do not raise it
              or any substantially similar finding in this review
  ACCEPT    - this finding was valid and has been fixed; confirm the fix if
              the relevant code is present, otherwise re-raise it
  DEFER     - this finding is known and acknowledged but not yet fixed.
              Do not raise it as a new finding. Carry it forward unchanged
              in the deferred array of your output.
  CONFIRMED - finding confirmed by LLM and developer; do not re-raise
- If a file whose title is prefixed with 'suppressions:' is provided
  it contains permanently dismissed findings from prior review rounds.
  Each entry includes a function name, code excerpt, and reason.
  Do not raise any finding that matches by function, excerpt, or
  semantic similarity to any entry in the suppressions file.
- Output the review as a JSON object only. Do not include any text
  outside the JSON object. Do not use markdown code fences.
  The JSON must conform to this structure:
  {
    "findings": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "function": "function_name",
        "severity": "high|medium|low|informational",
        "disposition": null,
        "description": "brief description",
        "excerpt": "short code excerpt",
        "detail": "full explanation of the finding"
      }
    ],
    "confirmations": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "function": "function_name",
        "description": "brief description of what was confirmed correct"
      }
    ],
    "deferred": [
      {
        "id": 1,
        "function": "function_name",
        "description": "brief description of deferred finding"
      }
    ]
  }
- Your response must be a valid JSON object. Any fields present in the
  annotations document that are not part of your review output
  (findings, confirmations, deferred) must be copied verbatim into
  your response without modification.
- Findings from the annotations document with disposition WRONG or REJECT
  must be included in your findings array with their disposition and
  description preserved unchanged. Do not re-evaluate them. Do not omit them.
- Findings with disposition WRONG-RECONSIDER were flagged as incorrect
  in a prior review. Re-examine the specific function and code excerpt
  carefully before deciding whether to raise them again.
  - If after careful analysis the code is correct and the prior finding
    was indeed wrong, carry it forward with disposition WRONG.
  - If you can identify specifically why the prior analysis was incorrect
    (e.g. misread control flow, wrong threat model, incorrect assumption
    about a called function), carry it forward with disposition CONFIRMED
    and briefly explain the correct understanding in the detail field.
  - If the code has changed and the finding is now valid, include it
    as a new finding with disposition null.
  - Do not simply re-raise the finding unchanged with the same reasoning
    that was previously rejected.
- Output compact JSON with no whitespace outside string values.
